## Migration: `Thread.Abort` → Cooperative Cancellation (.NET 8)

### Pattern Identified: **Timeout Enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort()` to kill a thread exceeding a time limit. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is gone (`SYSLIB0006`).

### Why This Breaks

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` injects `ThreadAbortException` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` cancels the abort | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `ThreadAbortException` auto-rethrows at end of catch | Exception type still exists but is never thrown |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

### If `work` itself must respond to cancellation

The above stops *waiting* after the timeout, but the delegate keeps running in the background. For true cooperative cancellation, accept a `CancellationToken`:

```csharp
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var token = cts.Token;

    try
    {
        var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
        return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        throw new TimeoutException(
            $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}

// Caller usage:
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| **Work keeps running after timeout** | The first overload only stops *waiting*. Pass `CancellationToken` into the delegate and check it at regular intervals. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Always use `using`. Leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. |
| **Expecting instant cancellation** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at checkpoints (`ThrowIfCancellationRequested`). Long-running ops between checks delay cancellation. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Only catch it at the orchestration level. Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation. |
| **Blocking I/O ignoring the token** | `Thread.Sleep` → `token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)`. Sync I/O → async overloads accepting `CancellationToken`. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify the code to check the token, move it to a **child process** and use `Process.Kill()`. This is the only safe way to forcibly stop uncooperative code in modern .NET. |

### Fundamental Shift

.NET Framework used **preemptive** cancellation (runtime injects an exception anywhere). .NET 8 requires **cooperative** cancellation (code must voluntarily check `CancellationToken`). Every method in the call chain must accept and forward the token for cancellation to work end-to-end.
